  INCIDENT CHANGELOG ANALYSIS
  ===========================
  
  Incident: IR-2024-0042 (Unauthorized Database Access via Compromised Service Account)
  Date of Incident: 2024-11-14
  Root Cause: Service account credentials exposed in public GitHub repository
  
  CHANGELOG RELEASES ANALYZED:
  ----------------------------
  
  v0.3.0 (2024-03-10)
  - Added health check endpoint
  - Fixed email validation bug
  
  v0.2.0 (2024-02-15)
  - Added POST /api/users endpoint
  - Added User case class with timestamps
  
  v0.1.0 (2024-01-10)
  - Initial release
  - GET /api/users endpoint
  - In-memory user storage
  
  ANALYSIS CONCLUSION:
  --------------------
  NO DIRECT RELATIONSHIP FOUND between the changelog releases and the incident.
  
  The incident (IR-2024-0042) was caused by:
  1. A service account password ('svc-analytics') being accidentally committed to a 
     public GitHub repository on 2024-10-28
  2. Lack of GitHub secret scanning to detect exposed credentials
  3. Absence of MFA enforcement on database access
  
  The changelog entries are all feature-focused releases:
  - API endpoint additions (POST /api/users, health checks)
  - Data model updates (User case class with timestamps)
  - Bug fixes (email validation)
  
  None of the releases address:
  - Credential management or security
  - GitHub secret scanning/prevention
  - Database access controls or MFA
  - Service account security policies
  
  RECOMMENDATION:
  The engineering team should consider adding security-focused releases to the 
  changelog that document:
  - Implementation of secret scanning
  - MFA enforcement for database access
  - Credential rotation policies
  - Security audits and penetration testing results
  
  This will help stakeholders understand the security posture improvements being 
  made to the platform.
  
